  "prompt": "Does every dog has rabies?",
  "response": "No, not every dog has rabies. Rabies is a viral disease that affects the central nervous system of mammals, including dogs. It is transmitted through the saliva of an infected animal, typically through bites.\n\nMost domestic dogs do not have rabies, especially in areas where rabies vaccinations are common and there is good public health infrastructure. Through vaccination programs and responsible pet ownership, the occurrence of rabies in dogs can be greatly reduced. It's important for pet owners to ensure their dogs are vaccinated against rabies and to avoid contact with wild animals that could carry the disease. If you suspect a dog may have rabies or has been bitten by a potentially rabid animal, it is crucial to seek veterinary assistance immediately.",
